[{"id":38999,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["B","A","C","D"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The change in energy is related to wavelength of photon emitted as:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>124</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1242</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>124</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p>Hence, option D is correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38963,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"We know\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{r}=0.529 \\frac{\\mathrm{n}^2}{\\mathrm{Z}} \\Rightarrow 8.48=0.529 \\frac{\\mathrm{n}^2}{1} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{n}^2=16 \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{n}=4\n\\end{aligned}$<br />We know\n$\\mathrm{E} \\propto \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}^2}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& E_{n^{\\text {th }}}=\\frac{E}{16} \\\\\n& x=16\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39058,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"The relation between wave length and energy of electron in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit<br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39012,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9b27988-c172-485f-aebf-6c7ad2bb2883-image.png\" style=\"width: 152px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2b7255cd-41a3-4dc3-b3d9-fb6f137d945d-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ba34010-3ffa-4016-8a44-dbe591995940-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9d742e7d-3651-480f-b86f-2f0a9d6e8009-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 130px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>We know the relation between radius and atomic mass number is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>A</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msup></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>ln</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>ln</mi><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mi>A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>ln</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;<br />It is similar to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;which is equation of line passing through origin.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39025,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>n</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>We know velocity of electron in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mtext>th&#160;</mtext></msup></math> shell of hydrogen atom is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>Z</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38961,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & 10.2 \\mathrm{eV}=\\frac{\\mathrm{hc}}{\\lambda} \\\\ & \\lambda=\\frac{1245 \\mathrm{eV}-\\mathrm{nm}}{10.2 \\mathrm{eV}}=122.06 \\mathrm{~nm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39061,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mi>n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mi>n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mi>n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mi>n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>π</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For a charge <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi></math> moving in a uniform magnetic field <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math><br /><br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/05287c6b-b2a9-4bee-9ed3-2acd5219046b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 156px;\" /><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>R</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>E</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br />By Bohr&#39;s quantization condition,&nbsp;<br /><br />Angular momentum <math><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br />Put <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>E</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39064,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>122</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Energy of an electron in n<sup>th</sup> orbit of an ion with atomic number&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi></math>&nbsp;is,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math><br /><br />for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mi>st</mi></msup></math> excited state of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>i</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>z</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math><br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#8756;</mo> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;Required energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39045,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>250</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>1700</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>220</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>2020</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"When electron pass through the mercury vapor, it losses some of its energy. The loss in <math><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi></math> of electron <math><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#8901;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0.7</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4.9</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> energy of radiation emitted <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>4.9</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> wavelength of radiation, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.24</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4.9</mn></mfrac><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mn>250</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38966,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{U}$","$2 \\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{U}$","$2 \\mathrm{E}=3 \\mathrm{U}$","$\\mathrm{E}=2 \\mathrm{U}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{F}=\\frac{\\mathrm{k}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{\\mathrm{r}^2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}^2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{KE}=\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{mv}^2=\\frac{1}{2} \\frac{\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{PE}=-\\frac{\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{TE}=\\frac{\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{2 \\mathrm{r}}-\\frac{\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{\\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{-\\mathrm{K}(\\mathrm{Ze})(\\mathrm{e})}{2 \\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{TE}=\\frac{\\mathrm{PE}}{2} \\\\ & 2 \\mathrm{TE}=\\mathrm{PE}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39009,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Both statement I and statement II are true.","Both statement I and statement II are false.","Statement I is correct but statement II is false.","Statement I is incorrect but statement II is true."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f855a3cf-53b5-48f7-afcd-4df54860504c-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 136px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>According to Bohr&#39;s model, when electron makes the transition from lower orbit to higher orbit, its energy can be given as</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>final</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>initial</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi><mi>f</mi></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>&nbsp;is Planck&#39;s constant.</p><p>Then,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mi>h</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Bohr&#39;s frequency condition is the law&nbsp;that state that the frequency of the radiation emitted or absorbed during the transition of an atomic system between two stationary states equals the difference in the energies of the states divided by Planck&#39;s constant.</p><p>Hence,&nbsp;Statement I is incorrect but statement II is true.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39080,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$36.3 \\mathrm{eV}$","$108.8 \\mathrm{eV}$","$122.4 \\mathrm{eV}$","$12.1 \\mathrm{eV}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$E_n=-13.6 \\frac{Z^2}{n^2}$\n$E_{\\mathrm{L}}{ }^{* *}=-13.6 \\times \\frac{9}{1}=-122.4 \\mathrm{eV}$\n$E_{\\mathrm{L}}{ }^{* *}=-13.6 \\times \\frac{9}{9}=-13.6 \\mathrm{eV}$\n$\\Delta E=-13.6-(-122.4)$\n$=108.8 \\mathrm{eV}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":38986,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let the higher state be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>.</p><p>The number of wavelengths emitted is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>For hydrogen atom,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mi>&#957;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>eV</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo stretchy=\"false\">&#8658;</mo><mi>&#957;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>E</mi><mi>h</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup><mi>Hz</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38996,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>R</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mi>R</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>As we know, radius of hydrogen like atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mi>R</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38954,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(A) is false but (R) is true","(A) is true but (R) is false","Both \\((\\mathbf{A})\\) and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) are true and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) is the correct explanation of \\((\\mathbf{A})\\)","Both \\((\\mathbf{A})\\) and \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) are true but \\((\\mathbf{R})\\) is not the correct explanation of \\((\\mathbf{A})\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"Assertion (A) is true because a sufficiently negative potential can repel and stop the emitted electrons from leaving the surface.\r\nReason (R) is also true because the stopping potential \\(V_{\\text {stop }}\\) varies linearly with the frequency \\(\\nu\\) of the incident light \\(\\left(V_{\\text {stop }}=\\frac{h}{e} \\nu-\\frac{\\phi}{e}\\right)\\).\r\nHowever, (R) does not directly explain why a negative potential suppresses electron emission; it only shows how much potential is needed for different frequencies.\r\nTherefore, both (A) and (R) are true, but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38998,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>For hydrogen like atom, the velocity of electron in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>h</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38969,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For Hydrogen like atom, energy emitted is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>C</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>h</mi><mi>ν</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>C</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Therefore, the  ratio<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>32</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>27</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>27</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>Hz</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>32</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>15</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39002,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(A) and (D) only.","(A) and (E) only.","(B) and (E) only.","(A) and (C) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Radius of nucleus is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>A</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msup></math>, where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;mass number of nucleus.</p><p>Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>A</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msup></math></p><p>Volume of nucleus is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>V</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>.</p><p>Now, the density of nucleus is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>M</mi><mi>V</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mi>&#960;</mi><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mi>&#960;</mi><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Thus,&nbsp;density is independent of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>.</p><p>Hence, only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>E</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are correct.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39074,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$207 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$465 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$310 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$620 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$E=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":39030,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>121</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>194</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>490</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>913</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>121</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38995,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let the electron jumped to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;excited state.</p><p>In the ground state, energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p>So, using relation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>75</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9375</mn><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>16</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>Now,&nbsp;angular momentum,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>828</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mi>&#960;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eVs</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>828</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39029,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>135</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>9</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>108</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mn>135</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39022,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>331</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>m</mi></math>. Ionization potential <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi>&#956;</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>eV</mi></mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub></mfenced></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>207</mn><mi>eV</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39049,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mi> </mi></math>","<math><mn>10</mn></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></math>, where <math><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub></math> are energies of photons from atom and nucleus respectively. <math><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub></math> is of the order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeV</mi></math> and <math><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub></math> in few <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>eV</mi></math>. So, <math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39020,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Time taken to revolve in circular orbit is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#969;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mi>v</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>22</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p>Now, current associated with the electron is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>T</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math><br />Hence, the current is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>112</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mA</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39075,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$8.1,0.67$","$8.1,1.2$","$6.4,1.2$","$6.4,0.67$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\frac{1}{\\lambda}=R\\left(\\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\\frac{1}{n_2^2}\\right)$ where $R=$ Rydberg\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { constant } \\\\\n& \\frac{1}{\\lambda_{32}}=\\left(\\frac{1}{4}-\\frac{1}{9}\\right)=\\frac{5}{36} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\lambda_{32}=\\frac{36}{5}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nSimilarly solving for $\\lambda_{31}$ and $\\lambda_{21}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\lambda_{31}=\\frac{9}{8} \\text { and } \\lambda_{21}=\\frac{4}{3} \\\\\n& \\therefore \\quad \\frac{\\lambda_{32}}{\\lambda_{31}}=6.4 \\text { and } \\frac{\\lambda_{21}}{\\lambda_{31}} \\simeq 1.2\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":